// GAMSAT Section 1 (Reasoning in Humanities and Social Sciences) question bank + taxonomy.
// Tagged on two axes: genre (the four GAMSAT S1 stimulus types) and skill (the reasoning tested).
// All stimuli and questions are original, written to mirror the style/difficulty of real S1; none are copied.
// Question object shape:
//   id            "gs1-prose-0001"
//   genre         prose | poetry | social_behavioural | graphic
//   skill         main_idea | inference | tone | characterisation | figurative_language | vocab_in_context | argument
//   stimulusId    groups questions under one shared stimulus
//   stimulus      { kind:"text"|"image", content, attribution }
//   stem          question text
//   format        single_best
//   options       array of option strings
//   answer        option index
//   explanation   human-authored, shown after answering
//   difficulty    easy | medium | hard
//   source        always "original"

const GAMSAT_S1_GENRES = {
  prose: "Prose fiction",
  poetry: "Poetry",
  social_behavioural: "Social & behavioural",
  graphic: "Graphic & illustration",
  testing: "Testing",
  calibration: "Calibration"
};

const GAMSAT_S1_SKILLS = {
  main_idea: "Main idea",
  inference: "Inference",
  tone: "Tone & attitude",
  characterisation: "Characterisation",
  figurative_language: "Figurative language",
  vocab_in_context: "Vocabulary in context",
  argument: "Argument & evidence"
};

const GAMSAT_S1_TAXONOMY = { genres: GAMSAT_S1_GENRES, skills: GAMSAT_S1_SKILLS };

const GAMSAT_S1_DIFFICULTIES = ["easy", "medium", "hard", "very_hard"];

const GAMSAT_S1_QUESTIONS = [
  { id: "gs1-poetry-001", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central preoccupation is", format: "single_best", options: ["the consolation that routine offers in the face of loss","whether a devotion that serves no purpose is ennobled or merely emptied","the indifference of the natural world to human persistence","the quiet dignity of labour performed without reward"], answer: 1, explanation: "B names the question the poem keeps open. D states one horn (dignity) as if settled, which the poem refuses; A reduces it to consolation; C (the uncounting bay) is a real but secondary note.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-002", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The final line, 'burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves', is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["a line poised between celebrating gratuitous excess and exposing futility","an ironic exposure of the keeper's belief that his work matters","an affirmation that selfless acts shine most when they expect no return","a lament that his effort has been spent on an empty bay"], answer: 0, explanation: "A, B and D each collapse the line to one reading; 'neither glad nor grieved' sustains both at once, so C, which names the balance, is precise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-003", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In context, the keeper's being 'neither glad nor grieved' is best captured by the single word", format: "single_best", options: ["phlegmatic","anhedonic","stoic","impassive"], answer: 3, explanation: "Impassive names a feeling that simply does not register, matching 'the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive'. Anhedonic is only the absence of pleasure, too narrow for a man who feels no grief either; stoic implies feeling endured or suppressed, though nothing here is being borne; phlegmatic names a calm temperament, a disposition rather than this emptiness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-004", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In context, that the light is 'surplus to need' casts the keeper's labour as", format: "single_best", options: ["quixotic","otiose","supererogatory","sisyphean"], answer: 2, explanation: "All four are advanced and plausible. Supererogatory (beyond what need or duty requires) matches 'surplus to need' without prejudging value; otiose (pointless), quixotic (deludedly idealistic) and sisyphean (futile, endless) each import a verdict the poem declines.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-005", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly concerned with", format: "single_best", options: ["the claim that true fidelity requires understanding what one preserves","the idea that the most reliable transmission may be the one least touched by a mind of its own","the way mechanical labour deadens the soul of the labourer","the suggestion that texts survive by luck rather than by care"], answer: 1, explanation: "B captures the paradox that his non-comprehension is why the chain held. A is its opposite; C moralises about the labourer beyond the text; D ('luck') ignores that it survives 'because of him'.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-006", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The simile 'the way a wire conducts a charge it never owns' implies that the copyist", format: "single_best", options: ["carried a meaning through himself without its ever becoming his","was indifferent to the harm his errors might cause","actively shaped the meaning he transmitted","resented being used merely as an instrument"], answer: 0, explanation: "C is the simile's point, conduction without ownership. A reverses it; B and D attribute attitudes (indifference, resentment) a wire cannot hold.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-007", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "Calling his accuracy 'not forbearance, but the absence of a stake' draws the line between", format: "single_best", options: ["caring about accuracy and being careless of it","altering the text on purpose and altering it by mistake","understanding what he copied and failing to understand it","resisting a temptation to alter the text and never feeling that temptation at all"], answer: 3, explanation: "Forbearance would mean holding back a real urge; 'the absence of a stake' means there was no urge to hold back, so A is the exact distinction. B, C and D substitute other contrasts the line never draws.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-008", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The closing stanza, that the chain's one link 'was made of a man who did not understand', is best read as", format: "single_best", options: ["celebrating his humility as the highest form of service","lamenting that his life was wasted on work he could not value","holding his non-understanding as both the guarantee of the text's survival and the emptying of his own part in it","crediting the institution, not the man, with the survival of the text"], answer: 2, explanation: "B holds the two readings the poem balances. A takes only the warm horn, C only the bleak one, and D contradicts 'because of him'.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-009", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central tension lies in", format: "single_best", options: ["the comfort of familiar objects after a bereavement","whether her refusal to change the house is fidelity or a self-made prison","the difficulty of grieving without the support of others","the way the dead continue to govern the living through habit"], answer: 1, explanation: "C is the explicit either/or, 'whether this is faith, or a cell'. D states one reading only; A reduces it to comfort; B introduces others' support, absent from the poem.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-010", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In 'To alter anything would be to admit a date', the word 'admit' most nearly means", format: "single_best", options: ["concede","broach","ratify","usher in"], answer: 0, explanation: "To admit a date here is to concede the fact of his death and its finality. Broach (to raise as a topic) is the near-miss; ratify (to approve formally) and usher in (to let enter, the literal sense of admit) both miss the act of acknowledgement.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-011", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The image that 'the rooms hold their breath' chiefly conveys", format: "single_best", options: ["the suspense of a household awaiting news","the tension between her and her visitors","the staleness of air in a house long shut up","a stillness that is also a refusal to let time resume"], answer: 3, explanation: "B fuses stillness with the willed arrest of time, the poem's centre. A invents an awaited event; C literalises to mere staleness; D imports interpersonal tension not present.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-012", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "At the close, 'she only winds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting', the woman is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["dutiful but awakening","faithful and at peace","devoted but unfree","loving and consoled"], answer: 2, explanation: "Devoted but unfree holds both halves the poem leaves standing: the care is real, yet the house is 'a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace'. The second word of each other pair fails, since 'she could not say, and does not ask' rules out peace, awakening and consolation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-013", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central claim is", format: "single_best", options: ["that careful observation is wasted on a world that will not hold still","that the worth of mapping lies in faithful witness to a moment, not in permanence","that all human knowledge is provisional and soon overturned","that the cartographer persists out of stubbornness rather than reason"], answer: 1, explanation: "B states the constructive turn, 'to fix a moment because it was'. A takes the 'folly' horn the poem answers; C generalises to all knowledge; D is the dismissive reading the poem reframes as honesty.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-014", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The detail that each chart is wrong 'before the ink is dry enough to fold' chiefly emphasises", format: "single_best", options: ["the speed with which his finished work is already falsified","the cartographer's haste and carelessness","the poor quality of his instruments","his refusal to wait for conditions to settle"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: the map is wrong almost at once, the tide outrunning him. A blames carelessness, though he is meticulous; C blames tools; D implies a choice to rush, but the point is the world's speed.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-015", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "Which person's work would the poem most regard as sharing the cartographer's purpose?", format: "single_best", options: ["an archivist who keeps old maps for the use of later scholars","a builder who raises a monument meant to outlast the centuries","a forecaster who predicts how the coast will look next year","a diarist who records one day exactly, knowing the entry will change nothing"], answer: 3, explanation: "The cartographer's worth is exact witness to a passing moment, not permanence or use, so the diarist matches. The builder seeks endurance, the forecaster prediction, and the archivist the cumulative use the poem sets aside.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-016", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The closing words, that the moment 'would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by', imply that without his record it would have", format: "single_best", options: ["been remembered inaccurately by others","recurred unchanged in a later season","passed with no one having marked that it was so","shown that the coast was never stable"], answer: 2, explanation: "B reads the moment passing unseen and unrecorded. A supplies inaccurate others; C contradicts the flux; D restates instability rather than the point about witness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-017", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem turns chiefly on", format: "single_best", options: ["the technical difficulty of cleaning an old painting without damage","whether restoration preserves a work or gradually replaces it with the restorer's own","the dishonesty of letting a restored work bear only the artist's name","the inevitable decay of all works of art over time"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the explicit 'kept, or made?' question. C (the label) is a consequence, not the centre; B reduces it to technique; D generalises to decay, missing the authorship puzzle.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-018", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "On the line 'so that the saved and the destroyed are one', rescue and effacement in her work are", format: "single_best", options: ["one and the same act, each achieved only in the doing of the other","two stages in sequence, the rescue coming before the loss","opposite results, only one of which finally happens","alike to the eye but opposite in their effect"], answer: 0, explanation: "The paradox is identity: to save is, in the same stroke, to efface. B makes them sequential, C makes them alternatives, and D makes them merely similar in appearance, each dissolving the oneness the line asserts.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-019", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "That she 'signs no name, and lets the label stand' is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["modest deference to the original artist's authorship","a legal requirement governing the attribution of restored works","a fear that claiming credit would damage her reputation","an evasion that leaves unresolved how much of the work is now hers"], answer: 3, explanation: "B fits the 'unanswered line' she works to the edge of. A reads it as settled humility the poem withholds; C invents a motive; D invents a rule.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-020", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's attitude toward her work is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["admiring of her skill and restraint","quietly accusatory of a kind of forgery","troubled, and deliberately without verdict","indifferent to the philosophical puzzle it raises"], answer: 2, explanation: "B matches the suspended 'unanswered line'. A resolves to praise, C to blame (forgery), and D contradicts the poem's evident absorption in the puzzle.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-021", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly concerned with", format: "single_best", options: ["that photographs distort the appearance of those they depict","that a fixed image can come to replace, rather than preserve, the living memory it was meant to save","that grief is eased by keeping mementos of the dead","that memory is inherently unreliable without physical aids"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the thesis: the keepsake 'quietly supplants' the face. B literalises it as distorted looks; C is the consoling view the poem undercuts ('hand me no album'); D reverses the poem, which says the aid harms memory.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-022", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In 'an afternoon gone white with distance', 'gone white' is best replaced by", format: "single_best", options: ["effaced","hoary","pallid","candid"], answer: 0, explanation: "The remembered afternoon has been blanked out by time, so effaced (rubbed away) fits. Hoary (white with age) and candid (from the Latin for white) play on the colour but miss the erasure; pallid (pale) is only a partial loss, not a blanking.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-023", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "That the living face is 'gone the more securely for the sight' is best understood to mean that", format: "single_best", options: ["seeing the photograph makes the loss feel more final","repeated viewing gradually wears out the photograph","the more one looks, the more one notices the photograph's flaws","the photograph, by fixing one look, makes the living face harder to recover"], answer: 3, explanation: "D names the paradox: the fixed image displaces recall. A is an emotional gloss, not the epistemic point; B and C literalise 'sight' as looking that damages the print.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-024", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's attitude toward the album is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sentimentally grateful for the comfort it brings","bitterly contemptuous of those who keep photographs","wary, treating the consolation it offers as a quiet betrayal","detached and merely analytical about memory"], answer: 2, explanation: "B matches 'what it saves it quietly supplants'. A is the surface attitude the poem refuses; C overstates to contempt of people; D understates the felt loss.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-025", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly about", format: "single_best", options: ["the disagreement between gentle and severe approaches to gardening","the way an apparent harm can be the very condition of later flourishing, and the unease of holding such power","the superiority of experience over sentiment in practical skill","the cruelty masked by the language gardeners use for their work"], answer: 1, explanation: "C holds both the flourishing-through-harm and the disquiet of unaccountable power. A frames a settled debate; B is narrow; D reads 'calls it love' as mere euphemism for cruelty, one horn only.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-026", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The line 'The wound was where the strength went' most nearly means that", format: "single_best", options: ["the plant's energy had been concentrated in the part he removed","cutting the plant weakened it, draining its strength","the gardener regretted the damage he had done","the plant was diseased at the point where he cut"], answer: 0, explanation: "A reads the paradox: last year's growth held the strength, so removing it frees the next. B literalises wound as weakening (the opposite); C imports regret; D invents disease.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-027", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "On the gardener's view, to spare the plant would be", format: "single_best", options: ["neither merciful nor harmful","both merciful and beneficial","cruel in seeming but kind in effect","merciful in seeming but harmful in effect"], answer: 3, explanation: "Sparing looks like kindness yet stunts the plant, so A. 'Cruel in seeming but kind in effect' is the inverted trap, describing the cutting instead; 'both merciful and beneficial' denies the harm; 'neither' empties the line.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-028", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The final line, that the garden 'never has a say in what it pays', chiefly", format: "single_best", options: ["observes that plants, lacking minds, are owed no consideration","condemns the gardener as a tyrant over his plants","introduces a note of disquiet about power exercised over what cannot consent","celebrates the gardener's complete mastery of his craft"], answer: 2, explanation: "A names the introduced unease without overclaiming. B overstates to condemnation; C is the dismissive opposite; D celebrates and misses the disquiet.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-029", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central tension is", format: "single_best", options: ["the transience of natural beauty","whether the snow's concealment is a falsehood or a mercy","the indifference of nature to human distinctions","the way appearances deceive us about reality"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the explicit 'Call it a lie... Or call it mercy'. B is secondary ('melts by noon'); C seizes on 'does not discriminate' but the question is evaluative, not about indifference; D is the 'lie' horn only.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-030", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In 'the same white sentence', the word 'sentence' most nearly means", format: "single_best", options: ["an edict","a locution","an adjudication","a periphrasis"], answer: 0, explanation: "The snow is laid alike over everything, so 'sentence' is an edict, a decree imposed uniformly. A locution (a turn of phrase) plays on the grammatical sense; an adjudication (a verdict on worth) is denied by the grace granted regardless; a periphrasis (a roundabout phrasing) is unrelated.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-031", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "That the snow's coat 'owes the truth of things below it nothing' means that", format: "single_best", options: ["the snow is indifferent to the value of what it covers","the beauty of snow is independent of what it falls on","the snow will inevitably melt and reveal the truth","the snow conceals the real condition of what lies beneath it"], answer: 3, explanation: "C is the line's point, concealment of the true state. A shifts to value-indifference; B to aesthetics; D is the next line's idea, not this one.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-032", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The final stanza, beginning 'Or call it mercy', functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["resolve the poem firmly in favour of the consoling reading","ironically undercut the idea that snow could be merciful","offer the merciful reading as a genuine alternative without discrediting the first","lament that the mercy is only temporary"], answer: 2, explanation: "B keeps both readings standing ('Call it a lie... Or call it mercy'). A over-resolves; C is the bleak horn; D shifts to transience.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-033", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem turns on the question of", format: "single_best", options: ["the ingratitude of students toward an ageing master","whether an artist's late roughness is decline or a deeper freedom","the inevitable physical decline that ends every career","the gap between popular taste and true artistry"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the explicit either/or. B misreads the grieving students; C states the decline horn as settled fact; D inflates a passing detail about critics.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-034", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The last line, that 'the hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike', is best read as", format: "single_best", options: ["the same outward sign is compatible with opposite inner truths, so it cannot settle the question","the master is physically frailer than he admits","freedom and decline are ultimately the same condition","onlookers cannot be trusted to judge an artist fairly"], answer: 0, explanation: "B is exact: an identical sign, two possible causes, so undecidable from outside. A literalises frailty; C overstates that the conditions are identical (only the sign is); D is a related but different claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-035", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "About the master's leaving phrases 'standing open', the poem leaves which possibilities open? I. that it is the decline of failing skill. II. that it is the freedom of mastered skill. III. that it is mere carelessness.", format: "single_best", options: ["I, II and III","I only","II and III only","I and II only"], answer: 3, explanation: "The poem hovers between decline (I) and freedom (II) and refuses to choose, but it never offers carelessness (III): the openness is pointed, not slack. So I and II only.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-036", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The phrase 'the rule let go by one who knows it now too well to need it' casts the master as having", format: "single_best", options: ["forgotten the rules he once knew","rejected the rules as worthless","so wholly internalised the rules that he no longer needs to apply them consciously","lost the capacity to follow the rules"], answer: 2, explanation: "D glosses 'knows it too well to need it'. A (forgotten) and C (incapable) are the decline horn; B overstates into rejection.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-037", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central claim is", format: "single_best", options: ["that forgiveness is always a disguised form of revenge","that to forgive openly is to claim a superiority over the forgiven, even when kindly meant","that one ought to forgive privately rather than aloud","that the man did not deserve to be forgiven"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the thesis ('not quite the equal's word'). B overstates to revenge; C turns an implication into a prescription; D is off-topic.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-038", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The images of 'the bench, the robe, the right to have condemned' present forgiveness as", format: "single_best", options: ["placing the forgiver in the position of a judge","evidence that the woman had a legal grievance against the man","proof that the man had committed a crime","something that should be a formal, deliberate act"], answer: 0, explanation: "B reads the courtroom metaphor as judicial authority. A and C literalise it into actual law and crime; D turns the image into a recommendation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-039", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The image of 'a hand laid on a head that did not bow' most precisely conveys that the forgiveness", format: "single_best", options: ["was refused outright by the man","was extended against the man's explicit wishes","met with a pride that prevented any gratitude","elevated her over a man who had neither sought nor submitted to it"], answer: 3, explanation: "B fits 'did not bow' (unsought, unsubmitted) with the height it 'conferred'. A overstates to active refusal; C judges the man; D claims an explicit refusal the poem does not state.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-040", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The concession 'Perhaps she meant it kindly. Even so' chiefly functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["withdraw the poem's criticism of her","reveal that her kindness was entirely feigned","grant her sincerity while insisting the act of forgiving still asserts rank","shift the blame from her to the man"], answer: 2, explanation: "D holds sincerity together with the structural point ('Even so'). A withdraws the criticism the 'Even so' preserves; B contradicts 'meant it kindly'; C redirects blame the poem does not.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-001", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best understood as a portrait of", format: "single_best", options: ["a generous friend whose loyal counsel is increasingly taken for granted","a man whose self-described virtue is, on his own evidence, a habit of steering others toward his own ends","the difficulty of preserving a friendship across great distances","the resentment that grows between friends of unequal success"], answer: 1, explanation: "B reads against the narrator: the cost to 'our Sundays', slipped in 'in passing', exposes control dressed as candour. A adopts his self-image; C and D are his framing, not what the passage reveals.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-002", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That he 'mentioned only in passing' the post's taking Daniel abroad most likely indicates that", format: "single_best", options: ["the cost he calls incidental was in fact his real motive, lightly disguised","the narrator had genuinely forgotten the post would take Daniel abroad","the narrator wished to spare Daniel's feelings about leaving","the narrator was too modest to dwell on his own sacrifice"], answer: 0, explanation: "D catches the irony: losing 'our Sundays' is the true reason, mentioned 'in passing' to hide it. A accepts his modesty; B contradicts what he plainly knew; C recasts it as kindness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-003", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's closing talk of 'the slow ingratitude that success breeds'", format: "single_best", options: ["indicates that Daniel has indeed become arrogant","accurately diagnoses why Daniel has grown distant","shows the narrator's hard-won wisdom about human nature","is a self-serving gloss on a coolness his own conduct better explains"], answer: 3, explanation: "A: the thinning thanks more likely track Daniel's dawning sense of being managed. B and D take the narrator's word for Daniel; C flatters the narrator.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-004", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The attitude the passage takes toward the narrator is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sympathetic to a misunderstood and loyal man","openly hostile, denouncing him as a villain","quietly ironic, letting his own words convict him","neutral, merely transcribing his account"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage never editorialises; the damning detail ('beyond the reach of our Sundays') is his own. A adopts his view; B overstates the temperature; D ignores how the details are arranged to undercut him.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-005", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "His insistence that 'honesty between friends must be complete' shows him to be", format: "single_best", options: ["candid and selfless","high-principled but self-serving","honest though tactless","scrupulous and consistent"], answer: 1, explanation: "He invokes a fine principle, but only to license the remark that served him, so high-principled but self-serving holds both halves. Each other pair fails on its second word: he is not selfless, tactlessness is not the point, and he is not consistent, since the principle never runs against his own interest.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-006", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Miss Pratt is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["someone whose genuine care is interwoven with loneliness and a hope not wholly disinterested","a kind neighbour whose goodness the street rightly admired","a calculating woman who befriended the man only for his possessions","a lonely woman indifferent to what others thought of her"], answer: 0, explanation: "C holds the braid of real care, her own cold house, and the managed grief over the jug. A makes her a mere schemer; B takes the street's verdict; D denies her evident attention to appearances.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-007", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The remark that 'a charity which warms the giver is charity still'", format: "single_best", options: ["endorses her visits as wholly selfless","claims that most charity is secretly selfish","condemns her for profiting from her own kindness","concedes a self-interested element while declining to call it hypocrisy"], answer: 3, explanation: "B captures the balanced concession. A ignores 'warms the giver'; C is harsher than the street's 'without unkindness'; D overgeneralises beyond this case.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-008", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Her being 'careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant'", format: "single_best", options: ["proves her grief for the man was entirely feigned","shows she valued the jug more than the man himself","reveals a self-consciousness about appearances that complicates, without cancelling, her grief","demonstrates her honesty about her own mixed feelings"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the managed display complicates but does not erase real feeling. A and B over-read it into fraud or greed; D reverses it, since she is managing appearances, not confessing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-009", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's stance toward Miss Pratt and the street is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["satirical, exposing the street's approval as foolish","wry but humane, noting the self-interest without withdrawing sympathy","tender and wholly uncritical toward everyone involved","coldly clinical about provincial hypocrisy"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the poised middle. B and D overstate the edge, since the narrator judges 'without unkindness'; C ignores the noted self-interest.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-010", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, 'the particular tiredness of the good' presents her weariness as essentially", format: "single_best", options: ["performative","lugubrious","fatuous","perfunctory"], answer: 0, explanation: "Performative catches a tiredness worn for the watching street, a badge of virtue put on for an audience. Lugubrious (mournful) misreads display as gloom; fatuous (silly) and perfunctory (cursory) miss that the weariness is shown, not slight.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-011", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly turns on", format: "single_best", options: ["the unfairness of interviews that reward confidence over substance","the importance of thorough preparation in winning a post","the cruelty of a panel that mocked an earnest applicant","the gap between the candidate's confident reading of the scene and what it actually conveyed"], answer: 3, explanation: "B is the dramatic irony. A and D draw morals the passage does not; C overstates the panel, which is 'more kindly'.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-012", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "'Thorough', said the second time more slowly, is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["blunt and critical","warm and sincere","polite but discouraging","casual and offhand"], answer: 2, explanation: "The slowed repetition keeps the courtesy of praise while draining its warmth, so polite but discouraging. Warm-and-sincere takes it at face value; blunt-and-critical overstates an open verdict the panel never gives; casual-and-offhand misses its loaded deliberateness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-013", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'look he took for admiration' is presented in a way that", format: "single_best", options: ["confirms the panel admired his plan","quietly warns the reader his reading may be mistaken","shows the panel disliked his plan intensely","proves the panel had already decided against him"], answer: 1, explanation: "C: 'he took for' flags the unreliability without asserting the reverse. A accepts his reading; B and D claim a certainty the text withholds.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-014", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The final sentence works chiefly to", format: "single_best", options: ["deliver the irony by letting the reader, not the candidate, learn the outcome","condemn the panel for the haste of their decision","suggest that the decision reached was unjust","imply that the candidate's letter will succeed"], answer: 0, explanation: "A names the device, reader-over-character knowledge. B and C editorialise; D contradicts the implied outcome.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-015", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's attitude toward the candidate is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["mocking of his vanity","indifferent to his fate","admiring of his confidence","pitying but not unkind, watching him misread a settled outcome"], answer: 3, explanation: "B fits the sympathetic irony. A overstates to mockery; C and D miss both the sympathy and the irony.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-016", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The scene chiefly conveys", format: "single_best", options: ["the practical difficulty of selling an old house","the insensitivity of the buyers toward a grieving seller","a woman's grief and buried guilt surfacing beneath a flat transaction","her relief at finally being free of a burdensome house"], answer: 2, explanation: "B: the boiler-and-curtains talk overlays a freighted history (the brother, the telephone). A takes the surface; C blames ordinary buyers; D misreads 'leaving everything' as liberation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-017", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Her not having spoken is, for her, chiefly a source of", format: "single_best", options: ["bereavement","compunction","resentment","vindication"], answer: 1, explanation: "Compunction, a prick of conscience over what one did or failed to do, names her guilt at the fatal silence. Bereavement is only the loss, not the self-blame; resentment and vindication point the feeling outward, away from her own omission.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-018", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The drawer that 'had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided... to behave'", format: "single_best", options: ["externalises her sense that the house is quietly releasing her","shows the buyers are skilled with old fittings","indicates she had exaggerated the house's faults","suggests the house is genuinely easier to manage now"], answer: 0, explanation: "D reads the projected significance, the house 'deciding' standing for her interior. A and C literalise the drawer; B credits the buyers.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-019", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing line, 'She was leaving everything', carries beneath its literal sense", format: "single_best", options: ["merely that the house was being sold furnished","a bitterness toward the buyers","a carelessness about her possessions","her surrender of a whole freighted past, not just the furnishings"], answer: 3, explanation: "B: 'everything' means the curtains and the past alike. A is the literal surface (the trap); C and D import attitudes the scene does not support.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-020", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's manner is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sentimental and openly mournful","detached and genuinely unfeeling","restrained, the feeling carried by understatement and juxtaposition","ironic at the woman's expense"], answer: 2, explanation: "B: the grief is conveyed by what is placed beside the sale, not stated. A overstates the openness; C mistakes restraint for absence of feeling; D mistakes the target.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-021", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is chiefly about", format: "single_best", options: ["a son's lasting resentment of a frugal father","the belated recognition of a love the child had misread as meanness","the universal tendency of teenagers to misjudge their parents","a father's failure to express his affection clearly"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the reversal the passage enacts. B reverses the ending; C generalises away the specific case; D blames the father, whereas the passage faults the son's earlier reading.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-022", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'the books were chosen, not the notes' means", format: "single_best", options: ["the true gift was the carefully chosen book, the money merely its wrapping","the father could never decide which book to give","the father had spent little thought on the gift","the books cost more than the notes were worth"], answer: 0, explanation: "C is the point. A reverses it; B invents indecision; D fastens on cost, which is not the measure here.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-023", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The money described as 'the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper' figures it as", format: "single_best", options: ["proof that the father was too poor to buy wrapping paper","the son's wish that the gift had been better presented","the father's resentment at having to give money at all","a stand-in for a tenderness he lacked the means to express more handsomely"], answer: 3, explanation: "C reads the metaphor. A literalises wrapping paper; B shifts to the son's preference; D imports a resentment the passage denies ('he did not defend himself').", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-024", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The contrast in the last lines, that he has the books still but cannot recall what he spent the notes on, chiefly", format: "single_best", options: ["shows the narrator was always careless with money","suggests he regrets the particular purchases he made","sharpens the reversal: what he scorned endured, what he prized vanished","implies the books were of little real use to him"], answer: 2, explanation: "B names the structural contrast. A and C miss it; D contradicts 'I have the books still'.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-025", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The older narrator's attitude toward his fifteen-year-old self is", format: "single_best", options: ["harshly self-condemning","rueful and tender, without excusing the boy's cruelty","amused and dismissive of a trivial episode","still privately aggrieved at the father"], answer: 1, explanation: "B fits the rue that still owns the cruelty ('said so... to his face'). A overstates to harshness; C trivialises; D reverses the reconciliation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-026", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The sketch is chiefly concerned with", format: "single_best", options: ["the way a relentless hospitality can be a means of mastering one's guests","the genuine warmth of an exceptionally hospitable host","the awkwardness of staying in another person's home","the ingratitude guests show toward generous hosts"], answer: 0, explanation: "B is the theme, conquest by kindness. A is Carver's reputation (the trap); C and D miss the power that the details trace.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-027", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing tide image, that his generosity 'lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was'", format: "single_best", options: ["praises Carver for benefiting everyone around him","accuses Carver of actively harming his guests","suggests that Carver's wealth was the source of his appeal","concedes his generosity is real while exposing its function as a display of ownership"], answer: 3, explanation: "D reads 'whose harbour it was' as the sting. A takes 'lifts every boat' as pure praise (the trap); B overstates to harm; C fastens on 'harbour' as mere wealth.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-028", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'Objection was provided for' tells us Carver had, in effect, every objection", format: "single_best", options: ["countenanced","brooked","forestalled","entertained"], answer: 2, explanation: "He anticipated and absorbed each preference so none could be raised: the objections were forestalled, headed off in advance. Brooked (tolerated), countenanced (permitted) and entertained (considered) all imply he let objections arise, the opposite of his method.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-029", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Being sent home as 'the occasion of someone else's enjoyment' implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the guests had enjoyed themselves more than they realised","the visit served Carver's pleasure rather than the guest's","Carver enjoyed his guests' company deeply","the guests felt guilty for not enjoying the weekend"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the point: the guest is the means to Carver's satisfaction. B reverses it; C sentimentalises; D invents guilt.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-030", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's tone toward Carver is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["amused but exacting","indignant and heated","fond but exasperated","detached and impartial"], answer: 0, explanation: "Amused but exacting fits the wry precision of 'conquered by kindness', light in manner yet sharp in its dissection. The other pairs each carry a false half: the tone is not heated, not fond, and not detached.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-031", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The man is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["a deeply compassionate man whose feeling others fail to appreciate","an artist too sensitive for the coarseness of ordinary life","a hypocrite who in truth feels nothing whatever","a man whose cultivated sensibility is a form of detachment from, not engagement with, others' feeling"], answer: 3, explanation: "B fits a feeling kept 'decanted' and performed for art. A inverts it; C overstates, since he does feel, but coldly and aesthetically; D adopts his own flattering self-image.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-032", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "His emotions 'kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display' are presented as", format: "single_best", options: ["pure and entirely sincere","suppressed and never felt at all","refined into a presentable display, drained of anything genuinely disturbing","unusually clear and easy for others to read"], answer: 2, explanation: "B reads the wine metaphor: decanted and de-sedimented means staged, with real disturbance removed. A takes 'clarified' as sincerity; C overstates to total suppression; D literalises clarity.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-033", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That a comforted friend 'went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble' implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the friends were genuinely comforted and grateful","his sympathy subtly made real suffering feel like an intrusion on his refinement","the friends were embarrassed by their own emotional weakness","he openly rebuked friends who burdened him with their troubles"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the shame springs from his manner, which makes real trouble seem coarse. A takes 'comforted' straight (the trap); C relocates the cause to the friends; D overstates to open rebuke.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-034", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, that he found 'the dying instructive' means he", format: "single_best", options: ["treated others' dying chiefly as material for his own edification","learned practical facts about illness from the dying","comforted the dying by instructing them","found visiting the dying tedious"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: 'instructive' marks the dying as a spectacle that improves him. A literalises it; C reverses the direction; D contradicts his appetite for such scenes.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-035", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's tone toward him is", format: "single_best", options: ["admiring of his refined sensibility","mournful at his essential loneliness","neutral and merely descriptive","coolly satirical, dismantling his refinement as self-regard"], answer: 3, explanation: "C fits the precise mockery of 'so fine a presence'. A accepts the surface; B sentimentalises; D ignores the edge.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-036", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best read as", format: "single_best", options: ["a victim of unlucky timing in a competitive workplace","a man genuinely wronged by a friend's unreasonable expectations","a man constructing, in real time, the excuses by which a betrayal is made to seem an accident","a scrupulous friend who agonised over a real dilemma"], answer: 2, explanation: "A: the whole passage is the building of a defence. B and C adopt his framing; D credits an agonising the breezy reasoning belies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-037", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Opening with 'betrayal is a strong word' is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a concession","a euphemism","a refutation","a recantation"], answer: 1, explanation: "He reaches for a milder term to soften the deed before naming it, the move of a euphemism. A concession would grant a point against himself; a refutation would argue the charge false; a recantation would withdraw a view he once held, none of which he does.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-038", genre: "prose", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'confidences, surely, are not contracts' is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a self-serving equivocation that treats a moral obligation as if it were merely a legal one","evidence that Marcus had no right to expect discretion","a sound legal distinction that settles the matter","a sign that the narrator had misunderstood the confidence"], answer: 0, explanation: "C: he swaps the moral force of a confidence for the narrower idea of a contract. A and B accept the move; D makes it innocent error.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-039", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "By 'accidents of timing' he recasts choices he made as mere", format: "single_best", options: ["volition","negligence","misfortune","happenstance"], answer: 3, explanation: "He dresses deliberate acts as chance, so happenstance. Negligence would still be a fault of his; misfortune makes it bad luck befalling him; volition (the will) is the very thing he is hiding, the opposite of accident.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-040", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The attitude the passage takes toward the narrator is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sympathetic to his genuine predicament","furiously condemnatory of his conduct","letting his own smooth reasoning expose the self-deception","genuinely undecided about his guilt"], answer: 2, explanation: "D: the irony lets his fluency convict him. A sympathises; B overstates the heat; C mistakes the irony for neutrality.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-041", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is chiefly concerned with", format: "single_best", options: ["a model of how siblings should fairly share an inheritance","the way an elaborate civility can be the very medium of an unspoken rivalry","a dispute over the monetary value of a family estate","the grief shared by two siblings after their mother's death"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the courtesy carries the contest. A takes 'fairness' at face value; C contradicts 'of no value'; D sentimentalises a scene built on wariness.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-042", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'each of them watched the other like a cat' conveys", format: "single_best", options: ["beneath the fairness ran a wary, competitive vigilance","the siblings were openly hostile to one another","the siblings feared being cheated by the lawyer","they were grieving too deeply to trust anyone"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the simile sets watchfulness under the courtesy. B overstates to open hostility; C and D misplace the wariness onto outsiders or grief.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-043", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Robert's declining first choice 'so that the generosity might be his'", format: "single_best", options: ["shows Robert's genuine selflessness","indicates Robert deferred to Helen out of simple respect","proves Robert wanted nothing from the house","reveals that even the concessions were moves in a contest for the higher ground"], answer: 3, explanation: "B: refusing the offer is itself a bid to be the more generous. A and D take the gesture at face value; C overstates his disinterest.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-044", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the division would seem to 'an observer... loving and a lawyer, prudent' implies", format: "single_best", options: ["the division was both legally sound and warmly affectionate","that lawyers are more honest than ordinary observers","the same conduct could be read as love or as calculation, and the passage leans to calculation","the siblings needed legal advice to divide the house"], answer: 2, explanation: "D: the doubled description exposes the calculation under the warmth. A takes both labels straight; B and C literalise 'lawyer'.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-045", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Of the clock, 'Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it' indicates that", format: "single_best", options: ["both genuinely wished the other to keep the keepsake","the polite offer masked that each in fact wanted it, and would not say so","neither sibling cared about the clock at all","the clock was too valuable for either to relinquish"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the offer is courtesy over real desire. A takes it straight; C contradicts that it 'carried her'; D contradicts 'of no value'.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-046", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing image, that 'the whole of what they would not say... stood, at last, in the room', chiefly", format: "single_best", options: ["renders their buried rivalry and grief wordlessly present without being spoken","shows the siblings finally voicing their long-held grievances","marks their reconciliation over a shared loss","introduces an outsider who breaks the deadlock"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: the unspoken becomes fully present, still unspoken. A contradicts 'would not say'; C sentimentalises; D invents an outsider.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-001", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is primarily concerned to argue", format: "single_best", options: ["that the orthodox defence of free speech confuses the value of truth with the value of liberty","that no right to speak can be founded on the speaker's being right without thereby ceasing to be a right","that tolerating dissent is justified less by its results than by what suppressing it reveals about the suppressor","that the worth of free speech lies in preserving the difference between genuine assent and mere compliance, not in the discovery of truth"], answer: 3, explanation: "B is the constructive conclusion. A and D are the critical steps mistaken for the thesis; C is a near-paraphrase with the emphasis shifted onto the censor's self-exposure rather than 'what we protect'.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-002", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's charge against the truth-based defence is that it", format: "single_best", options: ["protects only the opinions that prove true, and so secures nothing that actually stood in need of protection","treats as the normal outcome (truth prevailing) what the history of opinion shows to be the exception","makes the legitimacy of speech hostage to a verdict on its content that cannot be returned until after the speech has been heard","grants the censor the very authority it sets out to deny him, by allowing that error might rightly be silenced"], answer: 2, explanation: "C is the stated objection, the timing-and-grounding circularity. A (redundancy), B (empirical scepticism) and D (reflexive) are clever objections one could raise but not his.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-003", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's preferred ground for protecting speech?", format: "single_best", options: ["Many who are never silenced still submit to opinions they have not examined, so freedom alone secures no real assent.","One who is silenced may later, in freedom, arrive sincerely at the same view, so suppression need not foreclose genuine assent.","The censor often suppresses precisely the opinion he fears would persuade him.","Even under full freedom, the parties themselves can rarely tell being persuaded from being outmanoeuvred."], answer: 1, explanation: "A shows submission can convert to genuine assent, dissolving 'the censor forfeits the only proof'. B attacks a stronger claim than he makes; C supports him; D attacks the distinction's knowability, not its value.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-004", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "'The difference between agreement and submission' is the distinction between", format: "single_best", options: ["assent freely given and compliance produced by force","private conviction and public conformity","being persuaded and being defeated in argument","believing a claim and merely obeying a command"], answer: 0, explanation: "D is precise. The cruelest near-miss is C: being 'defeated in argument' is still inside the rational contest, whereas submission is yielding to power, not losing on the merits.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-005", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In calling such a freedom 'not a freedom but a wager', the author is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["restating the view in plainer terms","conceding a key point to that view","offering an analogy that supports it","drawing out an unacceptable consequence of the view he opposes"], answer: 3, explanation: "A: he follows the truth-defence to a consequence (the right vanishes once we are sure the speaker is wrong) and rejects it. B, C and D mistake a reductio for concession, analogy or paraphrase.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-006", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best exemplifies what the author says we protect?", format: "single_best", options: ["a debate in which the prize goes to the most truthful argument","a censor who blocks a claim he privately fears is true","a state that permits a protest it is confident is mistaken, since silencing it would prove nothing","a voter who changes his mind after a persuasive speech"], answer: 2, explanation: "B protects even the believed-wrong, preserving the agreement/submission distinction. A is the rejected truth-defence; C is the censor; D is persuasion working, not the protection principle.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In allowing that, once the causes are laid bare, 'no room is left for blame', the author's move is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a refutation","a concession","an extrapolation","a recantation"], answer: 1, explanation: "He grants the opponent's pull before resisting it, a concession. 'Recantation' (withdrawing a belief once held) is the obscure trap; he never held the view. 'Extrapolation' tempts but he is granting, not extending.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's view of the relation between the causal explanation of an act and the responsibility for it is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the explanation leaves responsibility open, and responsibility leaves the explanation open","the explanation settles responsibility, but responsibility leaves the explanation open","the explanation leaves responsibility open, but responsibility settles the explanation","the explanation settles responsibility, and responsibility settles the explanation"], answer: 0, explanation: "'Leaves wholly open the further question' kills the first axis; nothing links the second, so the two are independent (D). Eliminating one axis still leaves two options.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one would the author most likely regard as committing the error he describes?", format: "single_best", options: ["a judge who, told of an offender's brutal childhood, records the conviction but shortens the sentence","a man who forgives a betrayal without asking why it happened","a scientist who refuses to study cruelty's origins for fear of seeming to excuse it","a historian who, having traced every cause of a massacre, concludes that none of those involved can be blamed"], answer: 3, explanation: "B mistakes a full causal account for exculpation. C is the opposite error; A does the right thing (explains yet convicts); D is forgiveness without explanation, off the axis.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-010", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of understanding as 'a solvent in which responsibility dissolves' casts explanation as something that threatens to ___ responsibility.", format: "single_best", options: ["exculpate","adumbrate","vitiate","reify"], answer: 2, explanation: "'Vitiate' (impair, nullify) fits 'dissolves'. 'Adumbrate' (foreshadow) is the obscure trap; 'exculpate' is the seductive near-miss, but one exculpates a person, not 'responsibility'; 'reify' is wrong.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-011", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The engineer who 'skimped on the steel' is introduced in order to", format: "single_best", options: ["concede that some failures cannot be judged in moral terms","establish that a complete causal account can coexist with full responsibility","contrast physical accidents with moral wrongs","qualify the claim that explanation never excuses"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: we know exactly why the bridge fell and still blame the engineer. A and C reverse the example's force (it draws a parallel, not a contrast); D misreads a supporting case as a qualification.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-012", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Calling the confusion 'not compassion but a failure of attention' implies that those who make it", format: "single_best", options: ["have not looked closely enough to see that two distinct questions are in play","are too kind for their own good","are deliberately dishonest about their motives","lack the knowledge needed to judge such cases"], answer: 0, explanation: "C: the fault is inattention to the two-question structure, not malice or excess kindness. A imputes dishonesty; B takes 'compassion' straight; D blames missing knowledge rather than attention.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-013", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The distinction between false and genuine humility turns ultimately on", format: "single_best", options: ["the sincerity of his self-deprecation","the degree of his self-deprecation","the words he chooses to describe himself","where the speaker's attention is directed"], answer: 3, explanation: "C is ruled out ('words may be identical') and D too. The real fight is sincerity vs attention: insincerity is the intuitive read, but the stated criterion is self-attention ('not thinking about its own height').", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-014", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The argument depends on assuming that", format: "single_best", options: ["pride is always a vice and humility always a virtue","humble people are usually praised in the end","the same words can express opposite inner states","most displays of modesty are insincere"], answer: 2, explanation: "A is load-bearing: if words underdetermine the state, only inner orientation can distinguish the two. B, C and D are never needed by the argument.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-015", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage commits the author to which? I. False modesty seeks the praise it pretends to refuse. II. One cannot know whether one's own humility is genuine. III. Outward behaviour is an unreliable guide to humility.", format: "single_best", options: ["I only","I and III only","II and III only","I, II and III"], answer: 1, explanation: "I and III follow (the hook awaiting contradiction; behaviour 'may be identical', so it underdetermines). II is the overreach trap: the passage distinguishes the states, implying they are tellable apart.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-016", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The self-deprecation described is best characterised as", format: "single_best", options: ["captatory","obsequious","sycophantic","ingratiating"], answer: 0, explanation: "All four mean roughly favour-seeking. The act angles to elicit a specific compliment, which is captatory (rare: seeking to capture favour). 'Ingratiating' is the near-miss; obsequious and sycophantic point at flattering a superior, which he is not.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-017", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say genuine humility 'has left the room before the compliment arrives' means that it", format: "single_best", options: ["is too shy to remain present for praise","departs as soon as others begin to flatter it","deliberately avoids situations where it might be praised","is not present to itself as an object of regard, and so is not waiting for praise at all"], answer: 3, explanation: "B reads the metaphor of self-forgetfulness. A and D make it social shyness or literal departure; C makes it a deliberate avoidance, still self-aware.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-018", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's attitude toward the falsely modest man is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["indignant and morally severe","sympathetic to a harmless vanity","wry and dryly perceptive, exposing a contradiction","detached and merely classificatory"], answer: 2, explanation: "B fits the cool precision of 'the subtlest form of pride'. A overstates the heat; C excuses him; D ignores the pointed exposure.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-019", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is", format: "single_best", options: ["that whatever is natural is generally good and whatever is unnatural is suspect","that whether something is natural does not settle whether it is good, though a narrower caution can be salvaged","that human beings should avoid interfering with natural systems","that nature is, on the whole, crueller than human contrivance"], answer: 1, explanation: "B captures both the refutation and the salvaged caution. A is the view refuted; C is the reverence the passage separates from caution; D overreads the examples into a verdict on nature.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-020", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The pairs 'disease... the vaccine' and 'cruelty between animals... the hospital' are offered to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["much that is natural is bad and much human good is unnatural, so naturalness cannot certify value","nature is, on the whole, a cruel system","medicine is in every respect superior to nature","humans should never interfere with natural processes"], answer: 0, explanation: "Each pair sets a natural harm against an unnatural good, breaking the natural-good link. A overgeneralises; B fastens on half the examples; D draws the opposite practical moral.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-021", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The remark that 'caution is not reverence' draws a line between", format: "single_best", options: ["cowardice and genuine respect","people who are careful and people who are careless","scientific and religious habits of mind","prudent humility about what we do not understand and the belief that nature carries moral authority"], answer: 3, explanation: "Caution rests on ignorance, reverence on nature's supposed authority. A misreads caution as fear; C is broader than the contrast; D loses it, since both reverent and prudent people may be careful.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-022", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the salvaged claim 'warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound' shows that the author's humility", format: "single_best", options: ["can be used to justify any conclusion at all","ultimately refutes itself on inspection","tells against complacent traditionalism as much as against reckless innovation","supports reverence for nature after all"], answer: 2, explanation: "Humility about limited understanding distrusts both meddling and complacent custom. A overstates into uselessness; C is not claimed; D is exactly what 'caution is not reverence' denies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-023", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The sentence beginning 'What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower' chiefly functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["abandon the author's own position","replace a rejected claim with a weaker one the author will defend","restate the opening claim in stronger terms","concede that the appeal to nature was right all along"], answer: 1, explanation: "D: he trades the refuted natural-good inference for a modest caution he endorses. A and B misread a narrowing for a surrender; C inverts the move (it weakens, not strengthens, the claim).", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-024", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the inference 'does not survive a moment's pressure' means that it", format: "single_best", options: ["collapses as soon as it is examined with any care","is offered too quickly to be sincere","is rarely made by serious thinkers","depends on physical force to be accepted"], answer: 0, explanation: "A reads 'pressure' as scrutiny. B makes it about the speaker's haste; C about frequency; D literalises pressure as force.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-025", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central contention is", format: "single_best", options: ["that consistency is the most important intellectual virtue","that open-minded people are usually mistaken","that one should change one's views as often as possible","that consistency is only the agreement of beliefs with one another, no guarantee of truth, and can entrench error"], answer: 3, explanation: "B states it. A is the view attacked; C mistakes responsiveness for restlessness; D misreads the praise of the open mind.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-026", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The miser and the fanatic are cited to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["such people are unusually logical","inconsistency is always preferable to consistency","one can be perfectly consistent and yet wholly wrong, so consistency alone is no merit","consistency tends to cause fanaticism"], answer: 2, explanation: "C is the point: flawless internal agreement, no contact with truth. A flatters them; B overstates the other way; D asserts an unclaimed causal link.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-027", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'something harder' the author would honour in place of consistency is", format: "single_best", options: ["the refusal ever to contradict oneself","holding one's beliefs answerable to the facts, and revising them when truth requires","defending a system that no fact can disturb","changing one's mind whenever one is challenged"], answer: 1, explanation: "D is the closing redefinition. A and C are the rigidity he criticises; B is mere instability, not answerability to evidence.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-028", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs' means that genuine inquiry", format: "single_best", options: ["treats consistency as something worth sacrificing when the facts demand a change","values consistency above every other consideration","abandons consistency altogether as worthless","regards correction as too expensive to undertake"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: consistency is the price one pays to get a correction right. B inverts the priority; C overstates; D reverses the willingness to pay.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-029", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The argument assumes that", format: "single_best", options: ["consistency and truth never coincide","most people are inconsistent most of the time","fanatics are never sincere in their convictions","beliefs can be evaluated against the world, not merely against one another"], answer: 3, explanation: "A is the load-bearing premise that lets 'agreement with the world' outrank internal agreement. B and C are not needed; D overstates (they may coincide, just not necessarily).", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-030", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "A 'self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb' is one that is", format: "single_best", options: ["admirably rigorous and well-defended","too complex for ordinary people to follow","internally coherent but sealed against correction","supported by overwhelming evidence"], answer: 2, explanation: "C reads it as coherence closed to revision. A takes it as a virtue; B shifts to complexity; D reverses it into being evidence-backed.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-031", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is that", format: "single_best", options: ["to tolerate a practice is a disguised way of endorsing it","toleration presupposes disapproval, so it is the opposite of endorsement, though it can decay into indifference","a society should forbid only those practices the majority dislikes","indifference toward a disliked practice is preferable to forbidding it"], answer: 1, explanation: "A holds both moves the passage makes. B is the error it corrects; C is a policy rule never offered; D inverts the warning against the slide into indifference.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-032", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "'There is nothing to tolerate in what one approves' supports the idea that", format: "single_best", options: ["toleration is meaningful only when its object is something one objects to","approval and toleration are simply two names for one attitude","people seldom in fact approve of what they permit","a tolerant person must stay neutral about whatever they allow"], answer: 0, explanation: "If approval leaves nothing to tolerate, toleration must apply to the disapproved. A reverses it; C is an empirical aside; D is the neutrality the passage rejects.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-033", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Toleration 'decays into mere indifference' when", format: "single_best", options: ["a society comes to approve the practice it once merely permitted","the state at last forbids the practice it had allowed","people grow steadily more vocal in condemning the practice","the disapproval that toleration restrained gradually fades, leaving only the habit of permitting"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the restraint acts on nothing once the disapproval thins. A is a different end-state (approval); B is the opposite drift; C strengthens the disapproval.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-034", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the passage's view, toleration is marked by which combination?", format: "single_best", options: ["approval present, objection absent","approval absent, objection absent","approval absent, objection present but restrained","approval present, objection present"], answer: 2, explanation: "Toleration = disapproval (objection) held in check, with no approval. A is endorsement-like; B is indifference; D is incoherent for this account.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-035", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which best illustrates the decay the author warns of?", format: "single_best", options: ["a town that bans a club it once allowed","a town that keeps allowing a practice but no longer remembers that anyone objected to it","a town that debates a practice heatedly each year","a town that comes to celebrate what it once merely permitted"], answer: 1, explanation: "B is permission emptied of its lost disapproval. A is prohibition; C keeps the objection alive; D is the slide into approval, a different case.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-036", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Describing toleration as disapproval 'held deliberately in check' implies the tolerant person", format: "single_best", options: ["continues to disapprove but restrains acting on it","no longer disapproves of the practice","is genuinely indifferent to the practice","secretly approves of the practice"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: the disapproval persists, only restrained. A and C describe indifference; D describes endorsement.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-037", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main point is that", format: "single_best", options: ["criticism is a more effective teaching tool than praise","luck plays no real part in a cadet's performance","flight instructors should give cadets less feedback","the swings after praise and criticism are largely a statistical artefact, not evidence about feedback"], answer: 3, explanation: "B: the swings are regression, not the work of his words. A is the instructor's mistaken conclusion; C is unstated advice; D contradicts the mechanism.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-038", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The pattern would appear 'even if his words made no difference' because", format: "single_best", options: ["the cadets ignore whatever the instructor says","praise and criticism happen to cancel out","extreme performances are partly luck and tend to be followed by more average ones regardless of feedback","the instructor measures the landings inaccurately"], answer: 2, explanation: "C is regression to the mean. A posits inattention; B misdescribes the mechanism; D blames measurement, but the effect is in real, fluctuating performance.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-039", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The instructor's central error is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["praising cadets too rarely","treating a regression effect as a causal one","failing to keep proper records","being harsher than he ought to be"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: he reads a natural return toward average as the power of his words. A, C and D concern frequency, records or manner, not the inference.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-040", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most undermine the passage's explanation?", format: "single_best", options: ["Cadets who were praised improved far more, over many later flights, than cadets who were scolded","Cadets vary in natural talent","Good and bad landings occur in roughly equal numbers","Luck affects landings more than the instructor believes"], answer: 0, explanation: "A is a controlled comparison showing a real feedback effect, which the regression story denies. B, C and D are compatible with, or support, that story.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-041", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which everyday case shares the instructor's error?", format: "single_best", options: ["a gardener who waters plants and finds they grow","a coach who rests injured players and sees them heal","a student who studies more and scores higher","a patient who credits a remedy taken at his sickest for the recovery that followed"], answer: 3, explanation: "B: the sickest point is an extreme, and recovery (regression) follows regardless. The others involve a plausible genuine cause, not a regression artefact.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-042", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The metaphor 'a statistical tide' names", format: "single_best", options: ["the influence of the instructor's tone on morale","the gradual improvement of cadets over a course","the natural ebb and flow of performance around an average, independent of his intervention","the random errors made in recording scores"], answer: 2, explanation: "B: the 'tide' is regression, the rise and fall toward the mean. A credits his tone; C implies real learning; D is measurement error.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-043", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central point is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the charity is probably exaggerating its results","the ninety per cent figure cannot be interpreted without a comparison group, so it does not show the charity caused the recovery","ninety per cent is too low a rate to be impressive","charities should not report statistics to donors"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: with no baseline, the figure cannot be credited to the charity. A alleges dishonesty the passage avoids; C misjudges the issue; D is a broader rule than the argument supports.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-044", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'a number is not an argument' chiefly means that a statistic", format: "single_best", options: ["establishes nothing until it is set against the right comparison","is usually fabricated to persuade","is less convincing than a vivid example","should never be trusted on its own"], answer: 0, explanation: "B is the point: meaning comes from comparison. A imputes fabrication; C changes the subject to rhetoric; D overstates into blanket distrust.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-045", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The figure is 'a figure in search of a meaning' because", format: "single_best", options: ["the charity has probably inflated or selectively reported it","ninety per cent sounds impressive but is too vague a figure to act on","a bare percentage can never capture the human reality behind the cases","without the recovery rate of comparable families left unaided, it cannot be credited to the charity"], answer: 3, explanation: "C names the missing baseline that would give the number meaning. A imputes a dishonesty the passage avoids; B mistakes vagueness for the real gap; D is a general complaint about statistics, not this specific omission.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-046", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most undermine the charity's implied claim of success?", format: "single_best", options: ["Most families said they were grateful for the help","The charity helped more families this year than last","Families in the same crisis who received no help recovered within a year at about the same rate","A few of the families fell back into crisis after two years"], answer: 2, explanation: "A supplies the missing baseline and erases the charity's effect. B, C and D do not bear on whether the help caused the recovery.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-047", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which argument commits the same omission the passage identifies?", format: "single_best", options: ["a shop claims its prices are the lowest in town, and lists them","a tutor boasts that most of his students pass, without saying how many would have passed anyway","a doctor reports the exact dose she prescribed","a school publishes the names of its prize-winners"], answer: 1, explanation: "A lacks the no-treatment comparison, exactly the passage's flaw. The others make no causal success claim that a baseline would test.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-048", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the ninety per cent 'floats free' is to say it", format: "single_best", options: ["lacks the anchor of comparison that would give it significance","is suspiciously round and probably invented","changes from year to year","is too high to be believable"], answer: 0, explanation: "B reads 'floats free' as unmoored from a baseline. A imputes invention; C and D introduce variability or disbelief the phrase does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-049", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main point is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the successful do not really deserve their success","people should not argue about what others deserve","success is mostly a matter of luck rather than effort","the dispute persists because the two parties use deserve in different senses, each true on its own terms"], answer: 3, explanation: "B: it is an equivocation, not a contradiction. A and C take a side the passage refuses; D draws an unstated recommendation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-050", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The two senses of 'deserve' the passage distinguishes are", format: "single_best", options: ["one rooted in law and one rooted in morality","one expressed sincerely and one expressed with cynicism","one credited to the effort a person made, and one questioning whether the conditions for that effort were themselves earned","one concerned with wealth and one with social standing"], answer: 2, explanation: "B names the split the passage draws. A imposes a legal-moral distinction it never makes; C treats the two sides as honest versus dishonest, though both are 'right'; D narrows the rewards to wealth or status the text never specifies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-051", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Describing the quarrel as 'not a disagreement so much as a collision' implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the dispute is unusually bitter and personal","the parties are not contradicting each other but using one word for two things, so they talk past one another","one of the two sides must be lying","the question of desert has no possible answer"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: a collision marks claims that never meet. A reads it as heat; C ignores that both are right; D overstates into unanswerability.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-052", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the passage's view, the quarrel would end if", format: "single_best", options: ["the parties distinguished the two senses and saw that both claims can hold at once","one side finally admitted it was wrong","they agreed that success is undeserved","they agreed that success is fully deserved"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: separating the senses dissolves the collision. A presumes one is wrong; C and D pick a side the passage shows is half-right only.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-053", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which exchange shares the structure the passage describes?", format: "single_best", options: ["two people dispute whether a coin is weighted, and test it","two people argue over the result of a coin toss they both saw","two people agree a coin toss is fair and move on","two people argue whether a coin toss is 'random', one meaning unpredictable to us, the other meaning uncaused"], answer: 3, explanation: "A is a single word ('random') split into two senses, the same equivocation. The others are factual disputes or agreements, not equivocations.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-054", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the word 'has quietly split in two' means that it", format: "single_best", options: ["has fallen out of common use","has become a term of abuse","now carries two distinct meanings the disputants have not separated","no longer means anything definite at all"], answer: 2, explanation: "B reads the split as two unseparated senses. A and C change the subject; D overstates into total emptiness, whereas each sense is definite.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-055", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim is that", format: "single_best", options: ["accident reports are usually inaccurate about what happened","naming one necessary condition 'the cause' reflects our interests and where blame should fall, not a bare fact about the event","fires have too many causes to be explained at all","the frayed wire, not the oxygen, is the true cause of the fire"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: selection of the cause is an interested choice. A misses that the report is selective, not wrong; C treats selection as impossibility; D asserts the very privileging the passage calls a choice.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-056", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Treating the oxygen as a 'mere condition' is used to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["the line between cause and condition is one we draw, since the fire required both equally","oxygen matters less to a fire than the wire does","fires are physically too complex to understand","official reports deliberately omit important facts"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: equally necessary conditions, so the cause/condition split is ours. A accepts the ranking; C overstates; D alleges bad faith not claimed here.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-057", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the owner and the electricians each find their cause 'with perfect sincerity' most strongly implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["one of them must be lying about the fire","their disagreement concerns nothing real","sincerity guarantees that a causal judgement is correct","people can honestly select different causes because each fixes on the condition that suits a prior interest"], answer: 3, explanation: "B: sincerity plus opposite conclusions shows interest-shaped selection. A contradicts 'perfect sincerity'; C confuses honesty with accuracy; D ignores that each names a real condition.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-058", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing claim that the search for causes is 'a search for the responsible' means that", format: "single_best", options: ["blame has no place in an honest report","looking for causes is a waste of effort","we tend to designate as the cause the condition someone could and should have changed","the responsible party is always, in fact, the true cause"], answer: 2, explanation: "A: we pick the alterable, blameable condition. B does not follow; C is a recommendation the passage avoids; D collapses the selection/fact distinction it draws.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-059", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which best illustrates the passage's point?", format: "single_best", options: ["after a crash, investigators measure the skid marks precisely","after a crash, the driver blames the road and the council blames the driver, each citing a genuine factor","after a crash, two witnesses give identical accounts","after a crash, the cause is found to be a sudden tyre failure"], answer: 1, explanation: "A shows interested selection among real conditions. B is measurement; C is agreement; D simply names a cause without the selection problem.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-060", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the search is 'half secretly' a search for the responsible means the link to blame is", format: "single_best", options: ["present and operative, though not consciously acknowledged","openly admitted by everyone involved","deliberately concealed to deceive","imaginary and without real effect"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: it works beneath awareness. A contradicts 'secretly'; C imputes deliberate deceit; D denies its effect, which the passage affirms.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-001", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group: 18-29 reads 12, 30-44 reads 9, 45-59 reads 11, 60+ reads 15.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "Which comparison between the groups is best supported by the chart?", format: "single_best", options: ["the middle-aged groups read least because they have the least free time","reading falls steadily as age increases across the four groups","the oldest group reads about twice as much as the youngest","the youngest and the oldest groups both read more than the two middle-aged groups"], answer: 3, explanation: "The ends (12 and 15) both exceed the middle two (9 and 11), so A holds. B reverses the dip-then-rise shape; C over-reads 15 against 12 as 'twice'; D imports a cause the chart cannot show.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-002", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group: 18-29 reads 12, 30-44 reads 9, 45-59 reads 11, 60+ reads 15.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "Across the four groups, the pattern of reading is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a steady decline as age increases","a steady rise as age increases","lowest in the middle groups and higher at both ends","roughly the same across all groups"], answer: 2, explanation: "Values are 12, 9, 11, 15: a dip at 30-44 then a rise, so the ends exceed the middle. A and B impose monotonic trends; D ignores the spread from 9 to 15.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-003", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group: 18-29 reads 12, 30-44 reads 9, 45-59 reads 11, 60+ reads 15.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "The chart gives each group's mean but not the spread within it, so the chart cannot tell us", format: "single_best", options: ["which of the four groups has the highest mean","whether some people in the youngest group read more than some in the oldest","the rank order of the four groups by mean","how far the 60+ mean exceeds the 30-44 mean"], answer: 1, explanation: "A mean hides the distribution, so A (overlap between groups) is exactly what is lost. B, C and D can all be read straight off the bar heights.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-004", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group, a single snapshot in time.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "Which conclusion does the chart, on its own, actually support?", format: "single_best", options: ["in this sample, the 60+ group reported the highest mean","people come to read more as they grow older","reading keeps older people mentally active","the 30-44 group has the least free time for reading"], answer: 0, explanation: "B is all a single snapshot shows. A reads a longitudinal trend into cross-sectional data (different cohorts, not the same people ageing); C and D import unmeasured causes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-005", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group, measured once.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "To decide whether people come to read more as they age, one would most need", format: "single_best", options: ["the median rather than the mean for each group","a larger number of people in each age group","data on which genres each group prefers","the same people measured repeatedly as they grow older"], answer: 3, explanation: "A supplies the longitudinal data the snapshot lacks. B, C and D refine the same cross-sectional picture without addressing the cohort problem.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-006", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Table: 420 surveyed at the north end (beside the on-ramp) gave 62% support; 1180 at the south end gave 41% support.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "Taking both samples together, those who support the bridge are", format: "single_best", options: ["exactly half of those surveyed","a clear majority of the total surveyed","a minority of the total surveyed","impossible to estimate from the table"], answer: 2, explanation: "Support is about 260 of 420 plus 484 of 1180, around 744 of 1600, under half. The large southern sample outweighs the small northern majority.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-007", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Table showing northern respondents were surveyed beside the proposed on-ramp.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "That the northern respondents were surveyed 'beside the proposed on-ramp' most undermines confidence in", format: "single_best", options: ["the southern figure of 41%","the northern 62%, by oversampling those most likely to benefit","the total number of people surveyed","the honesty of the people who ran the survey"], answer: 1, explanation: "Sampling at the on-ramp gathers those who would gain, inflating northern support. The southern figure is untouched; the total is a fact; bias is not proven dishonesty.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-008", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Bridge survey table, north 62% support, south 41% support.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "A headline reading 'Most locals back the bridge' would be misleading chiefly because", format: "single_best", options: ["the larger southern sample opposes it, so the overall picture is the reverse","62% does not strictly count as 'most'","surveys can never measure opinion reliably","the bridge has not yet been built"], answer: 0, explanation: "The weighted total opposes the bridge, so 'most back it' inverts the result. B quibbles over a word; C and D are irrelevant to this table.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-009", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Bridge survey table by location.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "Which statement is best supported by the table?", format: "single_best", options: ["the survey was deliberately rigged","the bridge would do real harm to the south","northern residents are better informed about the bridge","opposition to the bridge is greater among those surveyed away from the on-ramp"], answer: 3, explanation: "The south (away from the ramp) opposes at 59%, supporting A. B, C and D infer harm, knowledge or fraud the table does not show.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-010", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Bridge survey table by location.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "To gauge genuine local opinion, the most important change would be to", format: "single_best", options: ["drop the southern sample as too large","survey more people at the on-ramp","survey both areas at locations unconnected to the bridge, in proportion to population","ask only those who say they will use the bridge"], answer: 2, explanation: "A removes the location bias and weights by population. B deepens the bias; C discards the representative sample; D narrows to an interested group.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-011", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Table: a clan-A man marries a clan-B woman and their children are clan C; B marries A, children D; C marries D, children A; D marries C, children B.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "Which one of the following must be true in the Garu system?", format: "single_best", options: ["a woman belongs to the same clan as her own children","a woman belongs to a different clan from her own children","a brother and a sister belong to different clans","a husband and a wife belong to the same clan"], answer: 1, explanation: "A child's clan is set by the father, and a mother's clan never matches it: a clan-B woman's children are C, a clan-A woman's are D, and so on. Siblings share their father's clan, and spouses are always of different clans, so the other three are false.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-012", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "A man's grandson (his son's son) belongs to the same clan as", format: "single_best", options: ["the man himself","the man's son","the man's wife","no one else in the family"], answer: 0, explanation: "A man of A has a son of C, whose son (a clan-C man's child) is clan A again, the grandfather's clan. The son is C, the wife B, so neither matches.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-013", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "Which one of the following is NOT possible in the Garu system?", format: "single_best", options: ["a grandfather and his grandson belonging to the same clan","two siblings belonging to the same clan","a husband and a wife belonging to different clans","a father and his son belonging to the same clan"], answer: 3, explanation: "No clan's children are its own (A gives C, C gives A, B gives D, D gives B), so a father and son can never share a clan. A grandfather and grandson do share one (A to C to A); spouses always differ; siblings always match.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-014", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "In this system, marriage and descent are such that", format: "single_best", options: ["a man and his children share a clan, but he and his grandchildren do not","a man, his children and his grandchildren all share one clan","a man and his children belong to different clans, but he and his son's children share a clan","all four clans may intermarry without restriction"], answer: 2, explanation: "A man (A) differs from his children (C) but matches his son's children (A). A reverses this; C ignores the shifts; D contradicts the fixed marriage rule.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-015", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "A child of clan A whose father is of clan C has a mother of clan", format: "single_best", options: ["C","D","A","B"], answer: 1, explanation: "A clan-C man marries a clan-D woman (row C), and their children are clan A, so the mother is clan D.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-001", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim is that", format: "single_best", options: ["to choose whom to trust the layman needs the very competence he lacks, so deference is itself a hard act of judgement","experts should not be trusted, since any of them may be a charlatan","deference to experts is always wiser than independent thought","the modern world has simply grown too complex to understand"], answer: 0, explanation: "B holds the paradox. A overstates into rejecting experts; C endorses the deference the passage complicates; D takes the framing remark for the thesis.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-002", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'difficulty it cannot itself resolve' is that", format: "single_best", options: ["experts frequently disagree with one another","laymen are too lazy to check what experts tell them","experts tend to overstate their own certainty","knowing which experts to trust presupposes the knowledge the layman, by definition, lacks"], answer: 3, explanation: "C is the circularity the passage names. A, B and D are real complaints about expertise but not the self-defeating difficulty it identifies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-003", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The point of listing 'the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement' is that these signs", format: "single_best", options: ["show that confident people are usually less competent","are worthless as any guide to competence","can be imitated by the incompetent as readily as earned by the able","should be ignored by the layman entirely"], answer: 2, explanation: "A: the charlatan can 'wear' them too. B and D overstate into dismissing the signs; C imports an empirical claim the passage does not make.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-004", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In calling deference 'one of [judgement's] hardest exercises', the author means that", format: "single_best", options: ["deference and independent judgement are simply the same thing","deferring well requires more independent judgement, not less","one should never defer to anyone under any circumstances","judgement becomes unnecessary once an expert has spoken"], answer: 1, explanation: "A: choosing whom to trust is a demanding judgement. B collapses the distinction; C and D draw extreme practical morals the passage avoids.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-005", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's worry?", format: "single_best", options: ["there exist reliable, layman-checkable track records that reliably distinguish the competent from the charlatan","experts are usually right within their own fields","charlatans are rarer than the passage implies","most laymen do, in practice, defer to experts"], answer: 0, explanation: "B gives the layman a way to judge without prior expertise, dissolving the circularity. A and C leave the selection problem intact; D is irrelevant to whether the selection is sound.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-006", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To tell 'the discipline from its counterfeit' is to distinguish", format: "single_best", options: ["a modern discipline from an old-fashioned one","a difficult subject from an easy one","an honest expert from a dishonest one","a genuine field of expertise from a convincing imitation of one"], answer: 3, explanation: "A reads 'counterfeit' as a fake field. B, C and D substitute difficulty, honesty or age for genuineness.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-007", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central contention is that", format: "single_best", options: ["careless driving should always be punished severely","luck plays a larger role in life than we usually admit","two equally careless acts are judged very differently because of an outcome neither controlled, which strains our principles either way","the law should treat all drink-drivers identically"], answer: 2, explanation: "B states the dilemma. A and D take practical sides; C is a general remark broader than the specific puzzle.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-008", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The dilemma the passage poses is that", format: "single_best", options: ["either the drivers were equally guilty, or they were equally innocent","either luck makes a moral difference, offending the rule that we answer only for what we control, or it makes none, and the law that parts them is unjust","either drinking is wrong, or driving is wrong","either we punish outcomes, or we punish nobody at all"], answer: 1, explanation: "B is the two-horned structure the passage builds. A flattens it to a verdict; C and D substitute unrelated either-ors.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-009", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The principle 'that we are answerable only for what we govern' means that", format: "single_best", options: ["we are responsible only for what lies within our control","we ought to govern our impulses more strictly","only governments are entitled to assign blame","we are responsible for everything we cause"], answer: 0, explanation: "A reads 'govern' as control. B moralises; C literalises 'govern' as government; D is the opposite (responsibility for all effects).", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-010", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The conviction the case is said to threaten is", format: "single_best", options: ["the belief that drink-driving is morally wrong","the conviction that luck does not really exist","the idea that the law should be internally consistent","the principle that responsibility extends no further than control"], answer: 3, explanation: "B: both horns wound the control principle. A is not in question; C and D are not the belief the passage says is at stake.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-011", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which pair best parallels the two drivers?", format: "single_best", options: ["a careful driver who avoids an accident through skill","two surgeons, one skilled and one careless, whose patients fare differently","two equally negligent surgeons, only one of whose patients happens to die","a reckless driver who is stopped before he can cause harm"], answer: 2, explanation: "A matches equal fault, unequal outcome by chance. B differs in skill (not luck); C and D lack the matched-carelessness structure.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-012", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up' means", format: "single_best", options: ["both arguments are equally persuasive","each of the two available conclusions damages a belief we want to keep","the dilemma has an obvious solution we resist","neither conclusion could possibly be true"], answer: 1, explanation: "A reads the 'horns' of a dilemma, both costly. B is about persuasiveness; C asserts an easy solution; D denies both, which the passage does not.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-013", genre: "testing", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The uncle's forgiveness is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["an act poised between a genuine release of grievance and a costless performance of magnanimity","a moving and wholly sincere release of an old grievance","a calculated fraud designed to deceive the assembled family","the confused gesture of a dying and failing mind"], answer: 0, explanation: "B holds the very ambiguity the passage refuses to resolve. A takes the 'beautiful scene' at face value; C overstates to fraud; D invents confusion.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-014", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that 'the will... was found to be unchanged' chiefly functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["be irrelevant to the meaning of the scene","prove the forgiveness was insincere","show the uncle had simply forgotten to alter his will","quietly check the generous reading, since the act conceded nothing material"], answer: 3, explanation: "A: the unchanged will complicates, without disproving, the generosity. B overstates to proof; C invents forgetfulness; D denies the pointed placement of the detail.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-015", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything' raises the possibility that the forgiveness", format: "single_best", options: ["was certainly heartfelt","confirmed that the nephew was guilty after all","may have been staged to win credit while surrendering nothing","was resented by the rest of the family"], answer: 2, explanation: "B is the suspicion the clause plants. A ignores it; C and D introduce the nephew's guilt or the family's feelings, not raised here.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-016", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the narrator 'cannot say; nor, I think, could he' most strongly implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the narrator is merely unwilling to judge his uncle","the uncle's own motive was opaque even to himself","no one present understood what had happened","the uncle was knowingly lying about his feelings"], answer: 1, explanation: "D: even the uncle could not have named his motive. A makes it reluctance; B asserts conscious lying; C shifts to the onlookers.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-017", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's tone is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["wry and suspended, declining to settle whether the act was sincere","bitterly accusatory toward the uncle","warmly approving of the reconciliation","indifferent to the family's feelings"], answer: 0, explanation: "C fits 'leaving others to decide what he had meant'. A approves; B condemns; D mistakes the careful withholding for indifference.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-018", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem's central tension is", format: "single_best", options: ["the duty to honour the war dead","grief at the deaths the memorial records","the durability of stone compared with human memory","whether the memorial preserves real remembrance or stages a sorrow that replaces it"], answer: 3, explanation: "A is the unresolved question. B and D take one earnest reading; C is a secondary motif, not the tension.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-019", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "That the visitors are 'moved less by them than by the act of moving' presents their grief as essentially", format: "single_best", options: ["maudlin","vicarious","self-regarding","ersatz"], answer: 2, explanation: "Their feeling turns on their own act of mourning rather than on the dead, so it is self-regarding. Vicarious (felt through another) points the wrong way; maudlin (tearfully sentimental) and ersatz (fake) name flaws the poem does not assert.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-020", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The lines 'the stone remembers nothing that we know, / and we remember nothing it is proving' chiefly mean that", format: "single_best", options: ["the inscriptions have worn away with time","neither the monument nor the visitors hold the actual lives it commemorates","the stone has outlasted the memory of those who carved it","the visitors have forgotten the history of the war"], answer: 1, explanation: "D: a gap on both sides, stone and mourners, around the real lives. A literalises wear; B and C narrow it to forgotten history or carvers.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-021", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The final stanza ('Still, better this than nothing; or perhaps / the nothing would at least be honest')", format: "single_best", options: ["leaves open whether the flawed memorial is better than nothing or worse than an honest blank","firmly concludes that the memorial is better than nothing","calls for the memorial to be torn down","celebrates the sorrow the memorial produces"], answer: 0, explanation: "B: 'or perhaps' suspends the verdict between the two. A resolves it; C overstates to demolition; D embraces the very sorrow the poem distrusts.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-022", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem's attitude is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["reverent and consoled","angrily contemptuous of the visitors","detached and purely descriptive","uneasy and self-implicating, distrusting the very grief it describes"], answer: 3, explanation: "C fits 'our easy sorrow', which includes the speaker. A is consoled; B is too hot and external; D ignores the implicated 'we'.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-001", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is often said that punishment is justified because it deters: the threat of suffering keeps others in line. But the account proves too much, for it would justify punishing a man known to be innocent whenever doing so would frighten enough others into obedience, and this we refuse, even when the sums favour it. The deterrent effect, then, cannot be the whole ground, since we hold to a limit it cannot supply. What the deterrence theorist has shown is not that deterrence justifies punishment, but that a practice already thought justified on other grounds also happens, conveniently, to deter.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is primarily concerned to argue", format: "single_best", options: ["that the deterrence theory, properly understood, actually justifies punishing the innocent","that punishing the innocent is wrong because it violates the rights of the individual","that deterrence is at best an incidental feature of a practice justified on other grounds","that no practice can be justified by its consequences alone"], answer: 2, explanation: "B is the closing reframe: the practice is justified elsewhere and merely 'happens, conveniently, to deter'. A inverts the reductio, which uses innocent-punishment against the theory; C states a true moral verdict but on a ground (rights) the passage never invokes, resting its case instead on 'a limit it cannot supply'; D over-generalises to all consequentialism, broader than the deterrence-specific target.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-002", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is often said that punishment is justified because it deters: the threat of suffering keeps others in line. But the account proves too much, for it would justify punishing a man known to be innocent whenever doing so would frighten enough others into obedience, and this we refuse, even when the sums favour it. The deterrent effect, then, cannot be the whole ground, since we hold to a limit it cannot supply. What the deterrence theorist has shown is not that deterrence justifies punishment, but that a practice already thought justified on other grounds also happens, conveniently, to deter.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In saying the deterrence account 'proves too much', the author objects that it", format: "single_best", options: ["exaggerates how effective the threat of punishment really is at preventing crime","would license punishing the innocent, an outcome we reject, so it cannot be the operative ground","rests on claims about human behaviour that have never been firmly established","assumes without argument that deterring others is a legitimate aim of the state"], answer: 1, explanation: "'Proves too much' is the logical charge that the principle licenses more than we will accept (punishing the innocent), so it fails as the ground (A). B and C raise the empirical effectiveness of deterrence, and D challenges its aim; each is a real objection one could press, but none is the over-licensing the phrase names.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-003", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is often said that punishment is justified because it deters: the threat of suffering keeps others in line. But the account proves too much, for it would justify punishing a man known to be innocent whenever doing so would frighten enough others into obedience, and this we refuse, even when the sums favour it. The deterrent effect, then, cannot be the whole ground, since we hold to a limit it cannot supply. What the deterrence theorist has shown is not that deterrence justifies punishment, but that a practice already thought justified on other grounds also happens, conveniently, to deter.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["In genuine emergencies we do knowingly impose grave burdens on the innocent to protect the many, and accept it","No deterrence theorist has ever actually recommended punishing an innocent person","Certainty of capture deters more reliably than severity of punishment","Punishment quite often fails to deter at all"], answer: 0, explanation: "The argument turns on the premise 'this we refuse, even when the sums favour it'. B denies exactly that refusal, so the reductio collapses. A concerns what theorists propose, not what the theory licenses; C is a detail about deterrence mechanics; D, that punishment often fails to deter, sits comfortably with the author's view that deterrence is incidental.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-004", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why does a promise bind? The familiar answer is that it creates an expectation, and that to break it is to disappoint someone who has arranged their affairs around your word. Yet this cannot be the whole story, for it would make the wrong of breaking a promise depend on whether the other had in fact relied on it, so that a promise no one troubled to count on could be broken at no cost. But we think otherwise: the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference, has still done what he ought not. The binding force lies not in the expectation aroused but in the act of binding itself, which the expectation merely, and usually, accompanies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim is", format: "single_best", options: ["that breaking a promise is wrong only when someone has relied upon it","that promises create expectations on which others are entitled to rely","that one should keep promises in order to avoid disappointing others","that the wrong of breaking a promise lies in the act of binding oneself, not in the expectation it arouses"], answer: 3, explanation: "C is the conclusion the passage builds to. A is the expectations account it rejects; B is true and stated in passing, but a premise, not the thesis; D is a prudential maxim, not the analysis of what the wrong consists in.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-005", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why does a promise bind? The familiar answer is that it creates an expectation, and that to break it is to disappoint someone who has arranged their affairs around your word. Yet this cannot be the whole story, for it would make the wrong of breaking a promise depend on whether the other had in fact relied on it, so that a promise no one troubled to count on could be broken at no cost. But we think otherwise: the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference, has still done what he ought not. The binding force lies not in the expectation aroused but in the act of binding itself, which the expectation merely, and usually, accompanies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The case of 'the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference' is offered to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["people often make promises they have no intention of keeping","reliance is in practice very hard to measure","a promise can be wrongly broken even where no expectation was disappointed, so expectation cannot be the source of the wrong","the wrong of breaking a promise depends on the promiser's character"], answer: 2, explanation: "The example is a counter-instance: a wrong with no disappointed expectation, which shows expectation is not the source (B). A makes a claim about frequency, C about measurement, and D about character, none of which is the logical role the example plays.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-006", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why does a promise bind? The familiar answer is that it creates an expectation, and that to break it is to disappoint someone who has arranged their affairs around your word. Yet this cannot be the whole story, for it would make the wrong of breaking a promise depend on whether the other had in fact relied on it, so that a promise no one troubled to count on could be broken at no cost. But we think otherwise: the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference, has still done what he ought not. The binding force lies not in the expectation aroused but in the act of binding itself, which the expectation merely, and usually, accompanies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The argument depends on assuming that", format: "single_best", options: ["most people do in fact rely on the promises made to them","an act can be wrong independently of any harm or disappointment it actually causes","promising is a distinctively human institution","the promiser's intentions are always known to the one he promises"], answer: 1, explanation: "The lucky careless promiser does wrong though nothing was disappointed, which only follows if wrongness can be independent of caused harm (A). B, C and D are each plausible background claims the argument never needs.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-007", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The objection that one who has nothing to hide has nothing to fear treats privacy as a screen for wrongdoing, valuable only to those with something to conceal. But this mistakes what privacy is for. A life lived wholly in view is not merely an exposed life; it is a different kind of life, for there are things one can only become, or think, or try, in the absence of an audience. To be always watched is to be always, in some measure, performing, and the self that performs is not the self that experiments. Privacy protects not the guilty secret but the unfinished thought, the half-formed self that publicity would freeze before it could take shape.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is chiefly concerned to argue", format: "single_best", options: ["that privacy matters because constant observation alters the self it observes, not because it conceals guilt","that people are entitled to keep their wrongdoing hidden from others","that state surveillance is an unjustified intrusion into private life","that people behave differently when they know they are being watched"], answer: 0, explanation: "B is the thesis: observation is constitutive, freezing 'the half-formed self'. A is the hiding-frame the passage rejects; C imports a political claim about the state the passage never makes; D states the supporting observation as if it were the point, stopping short of the claim that watching changes what the self can become.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-008", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The objection that one who has nothing to hide has nothing to fear treats privacy as a screen for wrongdoing, valuable only to those with something to conceal. But this mistakes what privacy is for. A life lived wholly in view is not merely an exposed life; it is a different kind of life, for there are things one can only become, or think, or try, in the absence of an audience. To be always watched is to be always, in some measure, performing, and the self that performs is not the self that experiments. Privacy protects not the guilty secret but the unfinished thought, the half-formed self that publicity would freeze before it could take shape.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The contrast between 'the self that performs' and 'the self that experiments' is drawn to establish that", format: "single_best", options: ["people grow dishonest when they know they are observed","performance is a worse way of living than authenticity","privacy is valuable chiefly to artists and original thinkers","observation does not merely reveal the self but changes what the self is able to do and become"], answer: 3, explanation: "The contrast makes observation constitutive rather than revealing (B). A reads 'performing' as dishonesty; C narrows the value to a special class; D smuggles in a ranking of ways of living the passage does not assert.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-009", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The objection that one who has nothing to hide has nothing to fear treats privacy as a screen for wrongdoing, valuable only to those with something to conceal. But this mistakes what privacy is for. A life lived wholly in view is not merely an exposed life; it is a different kind of life, for there are things one can only become, or think, or try, in the absence of an audience. To be always watched is to be always, in some measure, performing, and the self that performs is not the self that experiments. Privacy protects not the guilty secret but the unfinished thought, the half-formed self that publicity would freeze before it could take shape.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's defence of privacy?", format: "single_best", options: ["Many people who do no wrong nonetheless strongly desire privacy","Surveillance has become cheap and almost universal","Those raised wholly under observation develop selves as exploratory and unfinished as anyone else","A few people perform more freely, not less, before an audience"], answer: 2, explanation: "The defence rests on observation freezing the experimenting self; B says it does no such thing, dissolving the core claim. A actually supports the passage; C bears on prevalence, not value; D is the near-miss, about freedom in performance rather than the experimenting self being arrested.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-010", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity promises that careers be open to talents, that no one be barred by birth from the positions the talented may win. But the promise, kept, only pushes the inequality back a step. For the talents themselves are unequally distributed, and unequally cultivated, by families and circumstances no child has chosen, so that a race made fair at the starting line is run by competitors the prior years have already made unequal. To make the opportunity genuinely equal, one would have to equalise the conditions under which talents are formed, which is to say to reach back into the family itself, the very institution the principle was meant to leave untouched.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is", format: "single_best", options: ["that equality of opportunity should be abandoned as an ideal","that genuine equality of opportunity, pursued consistently, leads to intervening in the very family it was meant to leave alone","that talents are distributed unequally by birth and upbringing","that careers ought to be open to talents whatever a person's birth"], answer: 1, explanation: "A is the conclusion the regress drives to: equalising the formation of talents reaches into the family. B overstates, since the passage draws out a consequence rather than urging abandonment; C is a premise stated along the way; D is the principle under examination, not the conclusion.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-011", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity promises that careers be open to talents, that no one be barred by birth from the positions the talented may win. But the promise, kept, only pushes the inequality back a step. For the talents themselves are unequally distributed, and unequally cultivated, by families and circumstances no child has chosen, so that a race made fair at the starting line is run by competitors the prior years have already made unequal. To make the opportunity genuinely equal, one would have to equalise the conditions under which talents are formed, which is to say to reach back into the family itself, the very institution the principle was meant to leave untouched.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the principle, kept, 'only pushes the inequality back a step' is to claim that it", format: "single_best", options: ["removes one barrier only to leave an earlier, deeper inequality untouched","cannot be put into practice in any real society","favours the talented at the expense of the untalented","has never been sincerely attempted by any government"], answer: 0, explanation: "The barrier at the starting line falls, but the prior inequality in how talents were formed remains (B). A is about feasibility, C about who benefits, and D about historical attempts, none of which is the displacement the phrase describes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-012", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity promises that careers be open to talents, that no one be barred by birth from the positions the talented may win. But the promise, kept, only pushes the inequality back a step. For the talents themselves are unequally distributed, and unequally cultivated, by families and circumstances no child has chosen, so that a race made fair at the starting line is run by competitors the prior years have already made unequal. To make the opportunity genuinely equal, one would have to equalise the conditions under which talents are formed, which is to say to reach back into the family itself, the very institution the principle was meant to leave untouched.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["Families differ greatly in how much they cultivate their children's talents","Schooling could be equalised by the state without reaching into families","Some children overcome severe early disadvantage and still succeed","The talents that decide success are largely innate and barely shaped by upbringing"], answer: 3, explanation: "The argument needs talents to be family-formed; if they are largely innate (B), equalising the conditions of upbringing would neither be required nor sufficient, so the slide into the family does not follow. A supports the premise; C is anecdotal; D is the near-miss, since the passage's point about the family survives equalised schooling.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-013", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are increasingly asked not merely to tolerate ways of life we find mistaken, but to respect them; and the shift sounds like progress, a warmer and more generous attitude. Yet toleration and respect pull apart. To tolerate a practice is to put up with what one disapproves of, and so it presupposes the disapproval; to respect it is to set the disapproval aside, to grant the practice a standing one's own judgement denies it. The demand for respect, pressed universally, therefore asks us to stop judging at all; and a regard extended to every way of life without discrimination is not respect, which is earned and particular, but indifference wearing its clothes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is primarily concerned to argue", format: "single_best", options: ["that we ought to tolerate ways of life we disapprove of rather than respect them","that toleration is a warmer attitude than mere indifference","that the demand to respect all ways of life collapses, on inspection, into indifference rather than a deeper regard","that respect must be earned by the particular merits of a practice"], answer: 2, explanation: "B is the diagnosis the passage reaches: universal respect is 'indifference wearing its clothes'. A is a prescription the passage implies but does not make its point; C garbles the contrast (the passage calls universal respect, not toleration, the empty attitude); D is a premise about respect, not the conclusion.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-014", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are increasingly asked not merely to tolerate ways of life we find mistaken, but to respect them; and the shift sounds like progress, a warmer and more generous attitude. Yet toleration and respect pull apart. To tolerate a practice is to put up with what one disapproves of, and so it presupposes the disapproval; to respect it is to set the disapproval aside, to grant the practice a standing one's own judgement denies it. The demand for respect, pressed universally, therefore asks us to stop judging at all; and a regard extended to every way of life without discrimination is not respect, which is earned and particular, but indifference wearing its clothes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the passage's account, toleration differs from respect in that toleration", format: "single_best", options: ["involves a power to suppress that one chooses not to use","presupposes the very disapproval that respect sets aside","is extended to everyone, whereas respect is selective","is a colder attitude than respect"], answer: 1, explanation: "The drawn distinction is that toleration keeps the disapproval respect discards (B). A names a real feature of toleration, but not the contrast with respect the passage makes; C reverses things, since it is universal respect that the passage ties to indifference; D mislabels toleration as the colder of the two.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-015", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are increasingly asked not merely to tolerate ways of life we find mistaken, but to respect them; and the shift sounds like progress, a warmer and more generous attitude. Yet toleration and respect pull apart. To tolerate a practice is to put up with what one disapproves of, and so it presupposes the disapproval; to respect it is to set the disapproval aside, to grant the practice a standing one's own judgement denies it. The demand for respect, pressed universally, therefore asks us to stop judging at all; and a regard extended to every way of life without discrimination is not respect, which is earned and particular, but indifference wearing its clothes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's conclusion?", format: "single_best", options: ["One can set aside a particular disapproval on reflection while still judging discerningly overall, so respecting many ways of life need not mean ceasing to judge","People sometimes respect practices they have never had occasion to disapprove of","In ordinary speech 'tolerance' and 'respect' are used more or less interchangeably","Indifference and respect can produce the very same outward behaviour"], answer: 0, explanation: "The conclusion depends on the step that respecting all ways of life amounts to not judging at all; B blocks that step, so the slide into indifference fails. A is a side case; C is a verbal point; D, that the two look alike from outside, supports rather than weakens the author.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-016", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a temptation to think that what a man believes, so long as he keeps it to himself and acts on it only at his own risk, is his own affair. But no belief is truly private in its effects, for beliefs are the soil from which actions grow, and a habit of believing on insufficient evidence, indulged in the safe cases, does not stay quarantined there: it shapes the mind that will later face the cases that matter. The credulity we excuse in trifles trains the credulity that will not be harmless. What we owe is not a true belief on every question, which no one can promise, but the discipline of proportioning belief to evidence, even where the error would, this once, have cost nothing.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim is", format: "single_best", options: ["that one should believe only what can be conclusively proved true","that we are obliged to arrive at a true belief on every important question","that beliefs held privately have no effect on anyone else","that careless belief is culpable even in harmless cases, because the habit it forms will not stay harmless"], answer: 3, explanation: "B is the thesis: the habit of loose belief, indulged safely, trains a credulity that later does harm. A overstates into a demand for proof, which the passage replaces with proportioning belief to evidence; C is the view it refutes; D is exactly what the passage disclaims ('not a true belief on every question').", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-017", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a temptation to think that what a man believes, so long as he keeps it to himself and acts on it only at his own risk, is his own affair. But no belief is truly private in its effects, for beliefs are the soil from which actions grow, and a habit of believing on insufficient evidence, indulged in the safe cases, does not stay quarantined there: it shapes the mind that will later face the cases that matter. The credulity we excuse in trifles trains the credulity that will not be harmless. What we owe is not a true belief on every question, which no one can promise, but the discipline of proportioning belief to evidence, even where the error would, this once, have cost nothing.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of beliefs as 'the soil from which actions grow' chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["suggest that beliefs, once rooted, are difficult to change","argue that actions matter more than the beliefs that lie behind them","deny that any belief can be kept genuinely private in its effects","show that evidence is the proper nourishment of a belief"], answer: 2, explanation: "The metaphor makes belief the ground of action, so no belief is private in its effects (A). B inverts the emphasis; C presses the soil image toward rootedness, which is not its work here; D extends the metaphor attractively but is not the point the image is doing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-018", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a temptation to think that what a man believes, so long as he keeps it to himself and acts on it only at his own risk, is his own affair. But no belief is truly private in its effects, for beliefs are the soil from which actions grow, and a habit of believing on insufficient evidence, indulged in the safe cases, does not stay quarantined there: it shapes the mind that will later face the cases that matter. The credulity we excuse in trifles trains the credulity that will not be harmless. What we owe is not a true belief on every question, which no one can promise, but the discipline of proportioning belief to evidence, even where the error would, this once, have cost nothing.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["Most of the beliefs people hold never issue in any action at all","People are perfectly able to believe loosely in trivial matters while reasoning rigorously in the ones that count","Some false beliefs have, in fact, led to important discoveries","Good evidence is often very hard to come by"], answer: 1, explanation: "The argument rests on the habit of careless belief spreading from trifles to serious cases; A denies that spread, so the case falls. B is the near-miss, since the worry is a trained habit of mind rather than whether each belief acts; C and D do not touch the spillover claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
];

